y deposit excavated near Sparta more than fifty years ago, but they have remained unpublished until now. They number over 1,500 complete and fragmentary pieces. In technique, style, and iconography they form a homogeneous group unlike any other from mainland Greece. The large number of plaques and variety of types reveal a stable and vigorous coroplastic tradition in Lakonia during the late Archaic and Classical period. Heroic Offerings will be of interest to students and scholars of Greek history, art, and archaeology, to those interested in ancient religious practice in the Mediterranean, and to all inspired by Athens' chief political rival, Sparta. This volume received financial support from the Archaeological Institute of America"--cProvided by publisher.  aDescription based on information from the publisher. 0aVotive offeringszGreecezLakōnia. 0aHero worshipzGreecezLakōnia. 0aSacred spacezGreecezLakōnia. 0aTerra-cotta sculpture, GreekzGreecezLakōnia. 0aTerra-cotta plaqueszGreecezLakōnia. 0aExcavations (Archaeology)zGreecezLakōnia. 0aLakōnia (Greece)xAntiquities. 0aSparta (Extinct city)xReligious life and customs. 4aElectronic books.2 aMichigan Publishing (University of Michigan)epublisher.40zAccess to the Michigan Publishing online version:uhttps://doi.org/10.3998/mpub.3235848